"I've always hated Apple, but I heard their new cellphone had a really good camera, so I came and watched this video and I have to admit I simply blown away by this product! It looks incredible, for many reasons...

Firstly - that screen is amazing. It doesn't flicker, there's no reflection, it goes all the way to the edge... it doesn't even look like a screen, it looks like print! I've never seen anything like it before. It looks just like a special effect and not real.

As for the camera, I'm kind of in shock. I am not a cellphone user myself, and haven't looked at them for a while. Last time I checked, cellphones cameras were just a joke, with terrible quality and resolution. Not worth using except as a toy. But this camera is AMAZING - it looks as good as real camera, in fact it looks better than many real cameras. How can a camera so SMALL be so good?

And this leaves me very confused about *why* Apple have put such a sophisticated camera is a mainstream cellphone? This cellphone is going to be used by millions of people, the vast majority of whom have no interest in photography. So why is Apple giving them this ridiculously sophisticated camera? Is it trying to get everyone interested in photography? I just don't get it. It's almost insulting to photographers that the mass public are being given this great camera which they didn't ask for.

And then I have to mention that interface. WOW. The way you can just move your thumb and flick windows around like that. It's so powerful, so responsive. The interface almost looks more impressive than a real computer. It's quite incredible. To be honest I hate touchscreen, would never use it, and have no interest in it, which is part of the reason I've never even looked at smartphones before. But when I see a video like this I can almost begin to understand the appeal.

Generally, I think Apple are a terrible company who make shoddy, horrible, over-priced products that I always hate, and I wouldn't go near an Apple product. But I have to say, it looks like they've finally got their act together with this product. It's so advanced, it's like something out of a sci-fi film. Incredible.

I won't be buying a cellphone any time soon though. I still don't see any real point in owning one. I already have a telephone and computer. I don't need an all-in-one device, and certainly would not like to have to carry the gadget around with me everywhere I went. That would drive me nuts!"

"I like the notch. And as someone who listens to music and tv shows for HOURS everyday while I work, I can honestly say I've completely gotten used to the no headphone jack. It comes with Apple lightning ear buds, apple ear buds are always great. I keep those for the first half of the day while the battery is full (on my old iphone, new X battery lasts longer) then when I have to charge the phone, I switch to my bluetooth air pods and tadaa. No problem. You don't need a headphone jack. That's not to say that I haven't ever wished it had one, because if you forget the lightning ear buds or adapter, you are basically screwed when the bluetooth headphones die, but like I said, you get used to it. And you need to, cuz the 3.5mm jack is gone. I dislike how they went back to having to hold down programs in the carousel and then hit the minus button, that's a step back from just swiping the program up to close it. I also very much dislike how they removed battery percentage from the main screen. They should make it possible to replace the battery icon with just a percentage."

I much preferred the social aspects of the 5s over the self gratifying multitude of personalization of the note 5. The switch to the 7 from the 5s was less noticeable to me, considering they both functioned the same and had minor feature differences. The 7 plus had an obvious larger screen, which made it a plus. Other than that it was very much the same as the 5s.  

Having the X now, I am loving it! The notches, for me, add to the phone, rather than create an annoyance. Learning the new "controls" seemed to come naturally; I quickly found myself trying to use my work 7 the way a X functions and I became annoyed by the older way of doing things. The notches add straight forward swiping points and the upward swipe is what made the 7 annoying to use. I love swiping up to close permanently and temporarily. 

The added features, AR and facial recognition aren't a major factor for me. The screen and how the phone commands work, make the X more streamlined and hard to go back to an older version. The social side of iPhone is why I couldn't go to any other OS. Droid phones had to many distracting features and were antisocial in the fact that people can easily be caught up in there own phone decorating their screen and text messages were limited to a certain number of characters."

"Everyone wants a fingerprint reader on their smartphone. But in the iPhone X, there is not fingerprint reader. Face ID is good, but it\u2019s not perfect, but touch ID was perfect. And everyone will prefer touch ID to Face ID. As an electronics engineer, I get it to why apple removed touch ID. They removed it cus simply there was no place to put it. We can't put the fingerprint reader underneath the display cus that technology simply doesn't exist and it will be really difficult to invent that technology. Putting the fingerprint reader on the power button is theoretically ok, but practically there are lots of faults. Apple can\u2019t put a fingerprint reader on the back of the phone because it will ruin their whole seamless design, and it will look ugly. But I think i may have found a solution. At the back of the iPhone apple has their apple logo. That logo placement is perfect and its really easy to reach. Why can't we put the fingerprint reader on the apple logo. It would work perfectly. Fingerprint reader will be shaped to the apple logo, and made from ceramic. It will perfectly blend in, I will work just like touch ID, and it will not ruin the back design of the phone. The only downside is I don\u2019t know what effect it will have with wireless charging. But other than that, it\u2019s a perfect solution. \n-Randeera Liyanage-"

"The problem isn’t the notch. It’s the aspect ratio. Anytime you turn your phone sideways to get a bigger, more screen filling image, you will be disappointed with this phone. The screen isn’t any bigger than the older, smaller iPhones. Most content is 16x9 aspect ratio. This phone is 18x9 I think. So all 16x9 content will either have black bars left and right or, if you zoom in to fill screen, will have the top and bottom of the image cut off. Why you would ever make an 18x9 screen is beyond me. Just make it a little wider as well and the problem is solved. 

A lot of action movies have a 21x9 aspect ratio and this phone will actually provide a bigger image than the older phones if that’s what you are watching. But who watches action movies on a 6 inch screen. 

Tvs have a 16x9 aspect ratio. A while back they tried to make a 21x9 tv and it didn’t sell very well. They learned to just keep it 16x9."

"i'm a complete Apple guy, and the iPhone X looks awesome, but there are a few things that annoy me that I would think Apple would have realized. I really don't care about the price because every carrier has great financing options, including Apple, to get the phone (unless you're buying the phone outright). First, the notch...it seems really bothersome (for videos only)...you either have to deal with the notch interfering with videos or you have to deal with the black bars around the screen, either of which makes no sense. Second, why can't the phone just unlock with Face ID instead of the user having to swipe up after unlocking...touch ID is so easy...all you do is touch the home button and you unlock the phone and it goes to the home screen, or last app. Why can't face ID do this? Third, the app switching. Why must you swipe up and hold (or even swipe up and over), and then hit the red subtract button to get rid of apps? It is so much better to just swipe up and close apps. Apple should not have changed that. well, there's my thoughts"

"I am an apple geek, but I have to say this phone doesn't impress me much. I like the design, a mix of the various iPhones, well done, but I can't see a so dramatic change between OLED and LCD retina for now. It is better but not to justified the price. I don't mind too much about the notch until you want to watch a video, then the screen becomes same as a normal iphone 7 or 8. They need to work on it. When you move the iPhone X around you can see the oled screen is a bit bluish like lot of reviewers said already and this is not the best. I like the new gestures which replace the home button. But in general I have to say, I won't change my iPhone 7plus with the X for now. It is just a bigger iPhone 8 with better screen and slightly better camera then a 8plus(the stabilizer in the telephoto lens is not that great). I prefer reading and watching videos with the plus and as well if the X camera is much better when you take videos with it the camera app looks small like in the iPhone 8, much much better to have the plus as viewfinder. Surfing internet, reading through an app, watching videos, all of those actions still look better in the plus to me, the X don't take advantages of the \"larger\" (maybe just longer) screen. I will wait September to see the X plus 6.5inch, 6.1 and the 6.1 LED, if the rumors are true those are more interesting. This X looks like the iPhone 2 before the release of the 3, an experiment before the right one... doesn't worth 1000$ for me, much better the combo iPhone 8plus+iWatch 3+airpods. The last 2 are the best apple products until now (waiting for the iMac pro...)."

"You people say Apple fans are blind to subjective preferences, yet most Android fans seem to be blind to actual and provable facts. Apple has been, for instance,  years ahead of the competition with processors since the iPhone 5s came out, 4 years ago; yet you talk about specs, as if having more RAM or an extra MP would make your experience that much better (or at all, for that matter). I bet you people barely even know what a CPU is, or what makes it better or worse than others; have you ever at least read AnandTech’s reviews of iPhones’ CPUs and shit? Yeah, I didn’t think so… And I won’t even get into Apple’s new custom-designed GPU… You’re gonna tell me you don’t need that much power on a phone, now? Then, why the fuck would you need fucking 4–8 GBs of RAM on one! Basically, you don’t give a shit about specs when the iPhone’s winning, but specs are all that matter to you when Android phones have the lead? What kind of fucked up logic is that? I can’t even believe this shit…

And yeah, Samsung and others might've incorporated various features before Apple did, so what? Just compare Samsung’s facial recognition system to the iPhone X’s one; how could anybody possibly, even, fucking ever prefer to have something half-baked and defective a little before, than having something that actually works and makes your experience better, a little later? You gotta be fucking kidding me… Yeah, Apple clearly rushed iOS 11 as well and I hate that they did it; but it still runs fucking circles around the competition. I didn’t even give a shit about smartphones or computers before knowing Apple (yeah, I hated Windows before even knowing Apple existed); but Apple made technology magical and enjoyable for me, among other things; and if it weren’t for Apple, I would now be studying fucking linguistics instead of software engineering.

Still, the biggest “advantage” I see in Android would be its customizability, but wtf do I care about that? I don’t even change the wallpaper nor the icons’ position on my iPhone, so I’m pretty sure I wouldn’t change a fucking thing. Meanwhile, I’d suffer every single day from its lagginess, user-hostility, I would miss my favorite games and apps that are exclusive to iOS (the highest-end games and most professional apps for programmers and developers), and I’d lose all magic connection with my MacBook (and I’ll die before going back to that fucking nightmare called Windows); so, why would I ever switch? And… how could anyone ever say the iPhone’s behind? Because Galaxies got features nobody uses, and cuz it had a gimmicky and shitty facial recognition from before? Or is it cuz it’s got some extra GBs or RAM I literally wouldn’t even notice? I don’t really like iPhone X, btw; and I’m not even trynna defend Apple so much, as I’m honestly flummoxed by Apple haters/Android fans’ incoherence (and boy, do I fucking hate incoherence). If you’re a special kind of user, and for whatever reason the competition offers you something that Apple surprisingly doesn’t, then you might just be a different kind of user with different needs; but if you stupidly claim the iPhone’s objectively behind when facts prove otherwise, and you talk nonsensical shit about Apple without even knowing wtf you’re talking about, then you put the fucking “retard” in “retarded”, and it’s fucking pathetic and infuriating. I’d still prefer Apple if they were behind, and in some way, I would respect if you did the same; but I’d like it for real, actual reasons, instead of making up shitty alternative facts (yeah, I just said that:p)."

"Look ... I don't own it but I've owned three iPhones so far and I've played with it at the Apple Store.




I don't believe it's worth it. I don't want to compare it to an Android because the last time I've used Android was four years ago.




I just find it too expensive compared to the iPhone 8 or especially to the new price for the iPhone 7. Yes, it has gestures but so has BlackBerry. Personally I like the home button and the satisfying feedback it offers. I like the finger print sensor. I don't want to use gestures for everything as that's how the BlackBerry Passport worked and they're a pain in the ass to use when your fingers are wet and it misinterprets input.




The camera and everything may be great but it is $1000! You can get three iPhones 6 with this money, new. You can get two iPhones 7 used. It's $300 more expensive than the new iPhone 8 and brings just the Face ID and the new screen. Sorry but while technically is impressive, this is hardly value for money. 




I find more value for money in the 12.9 iPad + keyboard (that's cheaper btw) than in this phone. These are not phones anymore. These are fashion statements. These are in the same category as a watch or a pair of good shoes. From the entire line-up, I'm starting to find the iPhone the least useful device. The iPad can be used as a laptop replacement. The MacBook is still a workhorse for getting things done. The iPhone was great, at $600, not at $1000. 




The only good thing about the iPhone X is that the price of the old iPhones dropped or are going to drop significantly."

"Touch ID is indeed faster than Face ID when you compare the sheer speed, but in real life experience, Face ID is a lot more intuitive and practically more than makes up for  the slower process. For example, most of the time if not all, you don\u2019t unlock the phone right away till after you turn on the screen and check if there\u2019s new notifications, so with Face ID by the time you\u2019ve done checking, the phone is already done unlocking. Better yet, you can get right into the specific notification by tapping it since the phone is already unlocked VS having the extra step to unlock the phone on a Touch ID phone before you can launch the specific modification. As for the gestures, I\u2019ve always made my phones work just like that whenever I was able to jailbreak or root in the past. It becomes a second nature in literally no time and I couldn\u2019t be happier about it. Once go gestures, never go back."

"This is a disappointing review from one of the most followed YouTube tech reviewers. 

He didn't clarify that Apple customized and provided specs to Samsung and instead went with the lazy "good job Samsung" when reviewing the OLED. Apple did a lot of their own specifications and custom work to get the panel that accurate.

He also said the Apple display doesn't get as bright as the Note 8 which is objectively false, at least according to DisplayMate which rated the Apple OLED as the brightest ever tested in sustained brightness.

Source: "The iPhone X has a record high Full Screen Brightness for OLED Smartphones of 634 nits, which improves screen visibility in high Ambient Light. The Samsung Galaxy Note8 can produce up to 1,240 nits, but only for small portions of the screen area (Low Average Picture Levels) – for Full Screen Brightness the Note8 can produce up to 423 nits with Manual Brightness"

He said FaceID has trouble in sunlight...this isn't really true, but he said it as if it's a fact. Works perfectly for me every single time."

It then uses the standard RGB front-facing camera to track the user\u2019s face in real-time, enabling the Animoji feature. "I\u2019m a longtime iPhone user (since 3GS). Other than full screen, I don\u2019t see much new design-wise from my 6s. Apple was late to the full-screen party  and only came after the success of other brands. This review also makes too many excuses for iOS shortcomings, dismissing them with, \u201cWell, that\u2019s Apple.\u201d No, that\u2019s actually Apple being arrogant. Sure, the hardware chips and camera may be better than, say, the Note 8, but it was released 6 months later. Similarly, the Note 9 designers will be able to \u201cadjust\u201d for the X\u2019s features. And speaking of \u201cfeatures,\u201d Animojis is not one; those who think it is need to get a life; at best, it\u2019s a novelty, and certainly not one to justify buying an X. Overall, i found the X boring; this is the first time I\u2019m not \u201cupgrading\u201d to a new iPhone after one or two years. The X may, indeed, be the best iPhone yet, but it\u2019s far, far from being perfect, and note that he didn\u2019t say it\u2019s the best smartphone. I\u2019m waiting to see what comes out next year, from all brands. Given Apple\u2019s track record of recent years, I expect the XI (or whatever it\u2019s called) to be incrementally \u2014 but only incrementally \u2014  better, but still staid. And, FYI and FWIW, I\u2019m 70."

"You forgot to mention once you’re already in an app you can just swipe to the right at the bottom to go through your recent apps. It’s a lot easier.

I find the glass is amazing on the iPhone. It’s always smooth to the touch. Other than Samsung phones, I don't think I've used any other phone that has an amazing glass when touching and interacting with the display. Disregarding the resolution and numbers. The actual quality of the screen and glass is crazy good. Things look a little cinematic. I find Samsung phones have a similar feeling on their displays. And I do understand they’re the manufactured by Samsung. So it only makes sense. 

The stainless steel looks distracting and chrome like on the silver one. I’m glad I went with the slate.

I also find it weird the camera is on the right side instead of the left or at least centered. I cover it up and put smudges on it naturally because I’m right-handed. So when I pick it up or put it down my fingers are on it. Not a big deal. Just something I notice. 

When it comes to the notch, I like it to be honest. I like the smaller one on the Essential too. It looks futuristic to me. It’s different from what we’re used to. 

I do find that the iPhone handles notifications poorly imo compared to Android. I can check the notification in the app and that same notification will still be on the notification page. If the notification is many minutes old then you can dismiss them all with the X. Otherwise, there is no clear or dismiss button. 

I’ve always thought it was a bit dumb to keep most of the settings for apps in a separate settings application. Why can’t we access those dedicated settings for the app within the app we’re using like on Android? Why should we exit out of an app to go to the settings app just to change settings for the app I had to exit out of?

All in all, I think the phone is pretty sweet. Just waiting for my penguin Pixel Xl 2 to ship. *sigh*"

"I think to me the price is a huge sticking point for stuff that is available already and for stuff that isn't absolutely honed. We used to think paying \u00a3300 for a phone was insane. This tech is now less user friendly with the swipe gestures, the test was whether an elderly person could easily use it. I dunno, I've had iPhones for a while and used to be pumped for each one... This one and back to the 6s all don't do anything for me... they all seem very basic changes or ones that benefit apple but not me. The design of the overall phone is dated, the notch is not actually improving the phone as it actually cuts into things. The last few iPhones have pushed me to no looking at Android's highend market for my phone. I love tech, I buy all sorts of tech just to see how good it is, but the iPhone is almost predictable as soon as you see what features it will have, there isn't a WOW factor to the phones, it's more of a \"what? why would they do that?\" factor. for a \u00a31000, it's a little too steep, that's a massive proportion of my pay... for that, I expect a perfect user experience, I use my phone for videos and photos a lot. I've bought phones on their usability, their camera, their screens and their wow factor. This misses the mark on that (for me). The animoji are a gimmick that anyone could do on any phone, it's just they hyped this up to sound like it was new tech, it just smells of \"let's just pack it with random stuff that do things...\" I'm an apple fan and android, but apple just don't have that flair that they used to have, where each phone seemed like a step into the unknown. The tech is no longer leading edge, it's \"that'll do\" Face ID is not a logical solution, it's just the one that allowed them to get no bezels. I'm one person with my views, others will love it and buy it, I just hope that this doesn't set a precedent for the average phone cost going up to \u00a31,000, which will in turn make our phone contracts worth a lot more. It's insane that we used to think it was expensive to pay \u00a310 a month 10 years ago(Now I feel old) and \u00a325 sounds cheap now. people regularly pay \u00a330-\u00a350... there are other factors too, but I'm questioning when it will be that we realise these contracts are making us pay through our nose for something that actually doesn't cost that much to run. I hope we see quality products at reasonable prices back on the shelves soon. An iPhone 5 at the time of production cost about \u00a350-\u00a380 to produce and they've all been around that price since. I know this as I've studied Product Design and our Lecturer worked through getting one put together as if he was Apple, there are design costs too but with the sales of the phone, they become extremely small. So after all the costs surrounding designing, making, distributing, sales, they were making anything from 150% to 300% markup... I don't think it should be free phones, I understand they need to make a profit, but the price hikes are huge, but what we are receiving is actually not that proportion better. "Nice you pointed out that you don't need the 3D sensor for the Animoji. Didn't see any reviewers point that out. And it's the same thing with swipe-left/right at bottom to switch apps. Other iPhones can do that if it was programmed in the software. -- That Apple restricts some features/possibilities within the software to make their flagship "more" special is just disappointing. 

I've always used iPhone since 3GS model. I love iPhones (having owned also 4, 6 plus, and now SE), and mostly the reason of why I've been sticking to it is the ecosystem (together with iPad and Macs). Besides, upgrading to 4 was worth it (retina and front camera). Upgrading to 6 plus was worth it (bigger screen+battery finally). Buying SE (missed smaller sized phone). And now, I miss the bigger screen and planning to upgrade, but so far I'm not convinced if X is worth it. 

Is Animoji worth the extra cost? For me personally, No. Sure it's fun to have, but I don't need that.. Is Face ID worth the extra cost? Maybe it's more convenient, but like mentioned in the review, Touch ID works the same if not better and I don't mind using a finger to unlock the phone. 

Sure I could go for the 8 or 8 plus, but the design though with the same huge bezels. After all I pointed out, the ONLY reason for me to still buy an iPhone for my next phone is the ecosystem it is part of. Which leaves me the question: Do I really need a phone that is part of that ecosystem? I often use my phone to edit documents on iCloud, and I have headphones that take advantage of the W1 chip. Are these two features worth sacrificing for a new exciting experience with an Android-phone, or should I go for the 8/X that doesn't really offer any changes I have use for?"

"I think Apple has done well. 

I think the notifications needs cleaning up as you say. 

I think Apple needs to introduce auto unlock once Face ID knows it you. 

Apple should also include fast charging in the box. 

I love Air Pods and would a discount on them for buying the iPhone X. 

The Notch is fine but eventually I think this will be gone as well. 

Personally I’ve always preferred a Plus Model. 

I think next year will be even better. 

I also think Face ID will get faster next year. 

Face ID could also use gyroscopes to tilt when it’s flat on a table. This could perhaps allow the phone to look for you at a more shallow angle. 

So it’s a good move from Apple. 

I think the real pace is still being set by Samsung. If Samsung brings out the S9 at £900 with a better package than the iPhone X. Apple will have to react. 

Many people still think the S8 Plus and Note 8 is better than the iPhone X. 

Apple therefore has a good design now and a future look for the next couple of years. 

Apple will have to bring down its cost. This isn’t because Apple wants to be more cheap. This is purely because the S9 will out to grab as many Apple users as possible. 

If you look through the comments, you will notice the Samsung, Google and LG have great phones out as well. 

Competition is based on performance and price. 

Apple can’t sell phones which are £230 more expensive than Samsung’s flagship. This is literally suicide as Samsung will Just grab more and more customers."

"I would pay something like 700 € for this, since Galaxy S8 is already widely available for 600 € in Europe. S8 has 3,5 mm jack, no notch, arguably a better screen, fingerprint sensor, no wobling on a flat surface and such refinements.

If you compare X to Note 8 you will get the pen and larger and better screen. Not that I accept the atrocious price of Note 8, but still.

So given the price, which you cannot ignore, this phone is one of the worst releases in mobile phone history and I cannot believe people are buying this and telling themselves this phone is even decent. 

Of course I myself could release a new phone which is a tad better in every category than this - and those phones already exist - then put on a price tag of 1600 € and get raving reviews, but that one would still suck because it offers so little for a critically high price.

Reviewers should stomp this phone to the ground, but yet I hear much praise. This is only because of the status that Apple still currenly owns, but only a fool would buy X for just that status."

"No one really explained why they don\u2019t notice the notch when they use the phone. I have a theory: no one really does look at the status bar constantly. All the focus goes to the middle of the screen. It\u2019s also scientifically proven that the moment a person sees something new, their initial focus is all in the middle. That\u2019s why it\u2019s hard for some people to realise the big picture or their minds choose to see one thing when the whole thing is the correct perception. Going back to the notch, your focus stays in the middle of the screen. The only time you\u2019d notice the notch is when you are deliberately looking for something in the status bar. Be it time, battery, or network connection, you still don\u2019t look at those things constantly. That\u2019s why the notch seems to \u201cdisappear\u201d in use. Obviously, the notch doesn\u2019t literally disappear, but rather, our minds choose not to see the notch on top. That\u2019s why the notch is not a problem at all. If you come to think about it, the notch and ears are just merely extensions of the new screen. Don\u2019t think of it as a lose, but as a gain. You get extra screen on top, which can be used for then new status bar."

"I like the iPhone X! I got to put my hands on one at Best Buy. I took to the home gesture immediately, but I couldn't get the \"pick up and toss\" app switcher gesture. All in all it's a great iPhone. But, my 6s is still going strong, so I'm going to hold onto that. My 6s is my first ever iPhone after 6 years of Android phones, and while I miss some of Android's extra features, I like the stability of iOS. I have never had an Android phone not shit the bed after 12-18 months. It's just what Android does, it collapses under its own weight and bloat. A factory reset usually sorts it for a while, but then it's not gonna go another 12-18 months, more like 3-4 if you're lucky. I'm constantly blown away that my iPhone continues to be good. And I'm still blown away that having an icon below or to the right of a blank space is so hard for Apple. For a smartphone, particularly a big one, screen content should flow from the bottom to the top from user operated controls to content that is merely meant to be viewed. If I'm meant to interact with it, it should be closer to the bottom. If I'm not, push it to the top. So naturally I want my icons along the bottom, but not so much along the top."

"iPhone X is going to be obsolete by the time machine learning helps the camera / Face ID get anywhere close to the Pixel 2, and probably also before all apps are updated for the notch (some apps take years on things like this). Swiping is slower and less convenient than tapping, and Face ID is slower and less convenient than Touch ID. Even if the speed and accuracy improves, it's still a pain to have to hold your phone up to your face to unlock it. You can unlock phones with fingerprint readers while you're picking them up or taking them out of your pocket...

Getting to the top corners is really tricky on this phone, and the reachability gesture is ironically hard to trigger with one hand. Watching video is flat out bad on this phone because you're either getting massive bezels and a small image, or a notch cutout. iOS is... iOS.

It does do a lot really well (processor/performance, camera, etc.) but this just isn't worth $1,000. It feels like sacrifices on top of sacrifices as opposed to the most premium experience money can buy. If someone handed me one of these tomorrow I would sell it without a second thought. $1,000 is like 140 burritos (or >150 if we're buying the fast charger, which hilariously isn't included). I guarantee you I would be happier with my current phone and 140 burritos."

"Dude...........dude.......... I will first and openly admit, before I get a bunch of apple fans and Android haters, no phone is worth 1000 dollars. The functionality and look hasn't changed since the iPhone 5. I'm talking about color and art design. The cameras while impressive for all phones to fight, is really good. This one is probably just as impressive but man seriously? The price went up for, what to me at least as a over all user, an oled display and now a top firing speaker to run a duel speaker config. And not even good. I'm not even a Samsung fan boy anymore because even then I don't justify the design and other things that are not about this phone right now. While everyone has a right to spend their money on whatever they want and while I am clearly nobody to believe that this phone is useless to anyone except myself, I still can't believe you approved so little about this phone to justify $1000. There seriously has to be a line where enough is enough or this case there isn't enough to justify this price or idea that this is appropriate to the audience. But I digress as I prefer having a verbal conversation or rant about how I feel towards this phone than continue. Plus I am actually curious to see what thoughts and or mean comments I'm going to get for this one comment. Not trying to troll but from someone who expects a lot from an iPhone and apple themselves, I seriously am disappointed in this phone and this review. But maybe I'm not seeing the bigger picture. Someone can feel free to educate me a little as even I can be ignorant to the subject. Not a challenge or troll but just seriously wanting to hear a counter argument."

I've always hated Apple, but I heard their new cellphone had a really good camera, so I came and watched this video and I have to admit I simply blown away by this product! It looks incredible, for many reasons...

Firstly - that screen is amazing. It doesn't flicker, there's no reflection, it goes all the way to the edge... it doesn't even look like a screen, it looks like print! I've never seen anything like it before. It looks just like a special effect and not real.

As for the camera, I'm kind of in shock. I am not a cellphone user myself, and haven't looked at them for a while. Last time I checked, cellphones cameras were just a joke, with terrible quality and resolution. Not worth using except as a toy. But this camera is AMAZING - it looks as good as real camera, in fact it looks better than many real cameras. How can a camera so SMALL be so good?

And this leaves me very confused about *why* Apple have put such a sophisticated camera is a mainstream cellphone? This cellphone is going to be used by millions of people, the vast majority of whom have no interest in photography. So why is Apple giving them this ridiculously sophisticated camera? Is it trying to get everyone interested in photography? I just don't get it. It's almost insulting to photographers that the mass public are being given this great camera which they didn't ask for.

And then I have to mention that interface. WOW. The way you can just move your thumb and flick windows around like that. It's so powerful, so responsive. The interface almost looks more impressive than a real computer. It's quite incredible. To be honest I hate touchscreen, would never use it, and have no interest in it, which is part of the reason I've never even looked at smartphones before. But when I see a video like this I can almost begin to understand the appeal.

Generally, I think Apple are a terrible company who make shoddy, horrible, over-priced products that I always hate, and I wouldn't go near an Apple product. But I have to say, it looks like they've finally got their act together with this product. It's so advanced, it's like something out of a sci-fi film. Incredible.

I won't be buying a cellphone any time soon though. I still don't see any real point in owning one. I already have a telephone and computer. I don't need an all-in-one device, and certainly would not like to have to carry the gadget around with me everywhere I went. That would drive me nuts!

I like the notch. And as someone who listens to music and tv shows for HOURS everyday while I work, I can honestly say I've completely gotten used to the no headphone jack. It comes with Apple lightning ear buds, apple ear buds are always great. I keep those for the first half of the day while the battery is full (on my old iphone, new X battery lasts longer) then when I have to charge the phone, I switch to my bluetooth air pods and tadaa. No problem. You don't need a headphone jack. That's not to say that I haven't ever wished it had one, because if you forget the lightning ear buds or adapter, you are basically screwed when the bluetooth headphones die, but like I said, you get used to it. And you need to, cuz the 3.5mm jack is gone. I dislike how they went back to having to hold down programs in the carousel and then hit the minus button, that's a step back from just swiping the program up to close it. I also very much dislike how they removed battery percentage from the main screen. They should make it possible to replace the battery icon with just a percentage.

They use the depth sensor as a preprocess to get the face mask for digital puppeteering. It's extremely computationally intensive to do that purely through video and it takes a lot of data. Once they have the depth mask they can simply use a keypoint detector to pair with the 3d mesh for puppeteering, which is a lot faster than keeping the depth sensor running constantly throughout. They probably couldn't have done it with non-depth sensing iphones.

I absolutely agree! The X is a great leap forward. I came from a Note 5 to an iPhone 5s while I waited to get the iPhone7 plus. I much preferred the social aspects of the 5s over the self gratifying multitude of personalization of the note 5. The switch to the 7 from the 5s was less noticeable to me, considering they both functioned the same and had minor feature differences. The 7 plus had an obvious larger screen, which made it a plus. Other than that it was very much the same as the 5s.  

Having the X now, I am loving it! The notches, for me, add to the phone, rather than create an annoyance. Learning the new \controls\ seemed to come naturally; I quickly found myself trying to use my work 7 the way a X functions and I became annoyed by the older way of doing things. The notches add straight forward swiping points and the upward swipe is what made the 7 annoying to use. I love swiping up to close permanently and temporarily. 

The added features, AR and facial recognition aren't a major factor for me. The screen and how the phone commands work, make the X more streamlined and hard to go back to an older version. The social side of iPhone is why I couldn't go to any other OS. Droid phones had to many distracting features and were antisocial in the fact that people can easily be caught up in there own phone decorating their screen and text messages were limited to a certain number of characters.

I love Apple products but Apple is starting to miss in too many areas that should be slam dunks. I\u2019ve allowed it to slide for a while, but now it's starting to become a major issue. I'll share just a few of my gripes on this comment... 01) AirDrop inconsistencies. My iPhone X refuses to recognize my other Apple devices to AirDrop to them. This is something that should NOT be a headache... 02) Apple has no excuse for missing features that should be on EVERY phone. For example: OPTIONS. We should have Face ID and the fingerprint. We should have the option to swipe after Face ID unlocks the phone or to forgo the swipe option. We should be able to \delete all\ EVERYWHERE that it applies (i.e. multitasking, voicemail, etc). Everyone wants a fingerprint reader on their smartphone. But in the iPhone X, there is not fingerprint reader. Face ID is good, but it\u2019s not perfect, but touch ID was perfect. And everyone will prefer touch ID to Face ID. As an electronics engineer, I get it to why apple removed touch ID. They removed it cus simply there was no place to put it. We can't put the fingerprint reader underneath the display cus that technology simply doesn't exist and it will be really difficult to invent that technology. Putting the fingerprint reader on the power button is theoretically ok, but practically there are lots of faults. Apple can\u2019t put a fingerprint reader on the back of the phone because it will ruin their whole seamless design, and it will look ugly. But I think i may have found a solution. At the back of the iPhone apple has their apple logo. That logo placement is perfect and its really easy to reach. Why can't we put the fingerprint reader on the apple logo. It would work perfectly. Fingerprint reader will be shaped to the apple logo, and made from ceramic. It will perfectly blend in, I will work just like touch ID, and it will not ruin the back design of the phone. The only downside is I don\u2019t know what effect it will have with wireless charging. But other than that, it\u2019s a perfect solution. \n-Randeera Liyanage-

The problem isn’t the notch. It’s the aspect ratio. Anytime you turn your phone sideways to get a bigger, more screen filling image, you will be disappointed with this phone. The screen isn’t any bigger than the older, smaller iPhones. Most content is 16x9 aspect ratio. This phone is 18x9 I think. So all 16x9 content will either have black bars left and right or, if you zoom in to fill screen, will have the top and bottom of the image cut off. Why you would ever make an 18x9 screen is beyond me. Just make it a little wider as well and the problem is solved. 

A lot of action movies have a 21x9 aspect ratio and this phone will actually provide a bigger image than the older phones if that’s what you are watching. But who watches action movies on a 6 inch screen. 

Tvs have a 16x9 aspect ratio. A while back they tried to make a 21x9 tv and it didn’t sell very well. They learned to just keep it 16x9.

When you move the iPhone X around you can see the oled screen is a bit bluish like lot of reviewers said already and this is not the best. I like the new gestures which replace the home button. But in general I have to say, I won't change my iPhone 7plus with the X for now. It is just a bigger iPhone 8 with better screen and slightly better camera then a 8plus(the stabilizer in the telephoto lens is not that great). I prefer reading and watching videos with the plus and as well if the X camera is much better when you take videos with it the camera app looks small like in the iPhone 8, much much better to have the plus as viewfinder. Surfing internet, reading through an app, watching videos, all of those actions still look better in the plus to me, the X don't take advantages of the \larger\ (maybe just longer) screen. I will wait September to see the X plus 6.5inch, 6.1 and the 6.1 LED, if the rumors are true those are more interesting. This X looks like the iPhone 2 before the release of the 3, an experiment before the right one... doesn't worth 1000$ for me, much better the combo iPhone 8plus+iWatch 3+airpods. You people say Apple fans are blind to subjective preferences, yet most Android fans seem to be blind to actual and provable facts. Apple has been, for instance,  years ahead of the competition with processors since the iPhone 5s came out, 4 years ago; yet you talk about specs, as if having more RAM or an extra MP would make your experience that much better (or at all, for that matter). I bet you people barely even know what a CPU is, or what makes it better or worse than others; have you ever at least read AnandTech’s reviews of iPhones’ CPUs and shit? Yeah, I didn’t think so… And I won’t even get into Apple’s new custom-designed GPU… You’re gonna tell me you don’t need that much power on a phone, now? Then, why the fuck would you need fucking 4–8 GBs of RAM on one! Basically, you don’t give a shit about specs when the iPhone’s winning, but specs are all that matter to you when Android phones have the lead? What kind of fucked up logic is that? I can’t even believe this shit…

And yeah, Samsung and others might've incorporated various features before Apple did, so what? Just compare Samsung’s facial recognition system to the iPhone X’s one; how could anybody possibly, even, fucking ever prefer to have something half-baked and defective a little before, than having something that actually works and makes your experience better, a little later? You gotta be fucking kidding me… Yeah, Apple clearly rushed iOS 11 as well and I hate that they did it; but it still runs fucking circles around the competition. I didn’t even give a shit about smartphones or computers before knowing Apple (yeah, I hated Windows before even knowing Apple existed); but Apple made technology magical and enjoyable for me, among other things; and if it weren’t for Apple, I would now be studying fucking linguistics instead of software engineering.

Still, the biggest “advantage” I see in Android would be its customizability, but wtf do I care about that? I don’t even change the wallpaper nor the icons’ position on my iPhone, so I’m pretty sure I wouldn’t change a fucking thing. Meanwhile, I’d suffer every single day from its lagginess, user-hostility, I would miss my favorite games and apps that are exclusive to iOS (the highest-end games and most professional apps for programmers and developers), and I’d lose all magic connection with my MacBook (and I’ll die before going back to that fucking nightmare called Windows); so, why would I ever switch? And… how could anyone ever say the iPhone’s behind? Because Galaxies got features nobody uses, and cuz it had a gimmicky and shitty facial recognition from before? Or is it cuz it’s got some extra GBs or RAM I literally wouldn’t even notice? I don’t really like iPhone X, btw; and I’m not even trynna defend Apple so much, as I’m honestly flummoxed by Apple haters/Android fans’ incoherence (and boy, do I fucking hate incoherence). If you’re a special kind of user, and for whatever reason the competition offers you something that Apple surprisingly doesn’t, then you might just be a different kind of user with different needs; but if you stupidly claim the iPhone’s objectively behind when facts prove otherwise, and you talk nonsensical shit about Apple without even knowing wtf you’re talking about, then you put the fucking “retard” in “retarded”, and it’s fucking pathetic and infuriating. I’d still prefer Apple if they were behind, and in some way, I would respect if you did the same; but I’d like it for real, actual reasons, instead of making up shitty alternative facts (yeah, I just said that:p).

Touch ID is indeed faster than Face ID when you compare the sheer speed, but in real life experience, Face ID is a lot more intuitive and practically more than makes up for  the slower process. For example, most of the time if not all, you don\u2019t unlock the phone right away till after you turn on the screen and check if there\u2019s new notifications, so with Face ID by the time you\u2019ve done checking, the phone is already done unlocking. Better yet, you can get right into the specific notification by tapping it since the phone is already unlocked VS having the extra step to unlock the phone on a Touch ID phone before you can launch the specific modification. As for the gestures, I\u2019ve always made my phones work just like that whenever I was able to jailbreak or root in the past. It becomes a second nature in literally no time and I couldn\u2019t be happier about it. Once go gestures, never go back.

Great video as always. Just a side note about the use of Animoji on other iPhone: the Animoji feature does make use of the TrueDepth camera some of the time. Specifically, the phone uses the TrueDepth camera periodically to make a map of the user\u2019s face, especially on start up. It then uses the standard RGB front-facing camera to track the user\u2019s face in real-time, enabling the Animoji feature. So I\u2019m not sure it would have work so well on other iPhone without the TrueDepth camera.

I\u2019m a longtime iPhone user (since 3GS). Other than full screen, I don\u2019t see much new design-wise from my 6s. Apple was late to the full-screen party  and only came after the success of other brands. This review also makes too many excuses for iOS shortcomings, dismissing them with, \u201cWell, that\u2019s Apple.\u201d No, that\u2019s actually Apple being arrogant. Sure, the hardware chips and camera may be better than, say, the Note 8, but it was released 6 months later. Similarly, the Note 9 designers will be able to \u201cadjust\u201d for the X\u2019s features. And speaking of \u201cfeatures,\u201d Animojis is not one; those who think it is need to get a life; at best, it\u2019s a novelty, and certainly not one to justify buying an X. Overall, i found the X boring; this is the first time I\u2019m not \u201cupgrading\u201d to a new iPhone after one or two years. The X may, indeed, be the best iPhone yet, but it\u2019s far, far from being perfect, and note that he didn\u2019t say it\u2019s the best smartphone. I\u2019m waiting to see what comes out next year, from all brands. Given Apple\u2019s track record of recent years, I expect the XI (or whatever it\u2019s called) to be incrementally \u2014 but only incrementally \u2014  better, but still staid. And, FYI and FWIW, I\u2019m 70.

You forgot to mention once you’re already in an app you can just swipe to the right at the bottom to go through your recent apps. It’s a lot easier.

I find the glass is amazing on the iPhone. It’s always smooth to the touch. Other than Samsung phones, I don't think I've used any other phone that has an amazing glass when touching and interacting with the display. Disregarding the resolution and numbers. The actual quality of the screen and glass is crazy good. Things look a little cinematic. I find Samsung phones have a similar feeling on their displays. And I do understand they’re the manufactured by Samsung. So it only makes sense. 

The stainless steel looks distracting and chrome like on the silver one. I’m glad I went with the slate.

I also find it weird the camera is on the right side instead of the left or at least centered. I cover it up and put smudges on it naturally because I’m right-handed. So when I pick it up or put it down my fingers are on it. Not a big deal. Just something I notice. 

When it comes to the notch, I like it to be honest. I like the smaller one on the Essential too. It looks futuristic to me. It’s different from what we’re used to. 

I do find that the iPhone handles notifications poorly imo compared to Android. I can check the notification in the app and that same notification will still be on the notification page. If the notification is many minutes old then you can dismiss them all with the X. Otherwise, there is no clear or dismiss button. 

I’ve always thought it was a bit dumb to keep most of the settings for apps in a separate settings application. Why can’t we access those dedicated settings for the app within the app we’re using like on Android? Why should we exit out of an app to go to the settings app just to change settings for the app I had to exit out of?

All in all, I think the phone is pretty sweet. Just waiting for my penguin Pixel Xl 2 to ship. *sigh*

I think to me the price is a huge sticking point for stuff that is available already and for stuff that isn't absolutely honed. We used to think paying \u00a3300 for a phone was insane. This tech is now less user friendly with the swipe gestures, the test was whether an elderly person could easily use it. I dunno, I've had iPhones for a while and used to be pumped for each one... This one and back to the 6s all don't do anything for me... they all seem very basic changes or ones that benefit apple but not me. The design of the overall phone is dated, the notch is not actually improving the phone as it actually cuts into things. The last few iPhones have pushed me to no looking at Android's highend market for my phone. I love tech, I buy all sorts of tech just to see how good it is, but the iPhone is almost predictable as soon as you see what features it will have, there isn't a WOW factor to the phones, it's more of a \what? why would they do that?\ factor. for a \u00a31000, it's a little too steep, that's a massive proportion of my pay... for that, I expect a perfect user experience, I use my phone for videos and photos a lot. I've bought phones on their usability, their camera, their screens and their wow factor. This misses the mark on that (for me). The animoji are a gimmick that anyone could do on any phone, it's just they hyped this up to sound like it was new tech, it just smells of \let's just pack it with random stuff that do things...\ I'm an apple fan and android, but apple just don't have that flair that they used to have, where each phone seemed like a step into the unknown. The tech is no longer leading edge, it's \that'll do\ Face ID is not a logical solution, it's just the one that allowed them to get no bezels. I'm one person with my views, others will love it and buy it, I just hope that this doesn't set a precedent for the average phone cost going up to \u00a31,000, which will in turn make our phone contracts worth a lot more. It's insane that we used to think it was expensive to pay \u00a310 a month 10 years ago(Now I feel old) and \u00a325 sounds cheap now. people regularly pay \u00a330-\u00a350... there are other factors too, but I'm questioning when it will be that we realise these contracts are making us pay through our nose for something that actually doesn't cost that much to run. I hope we see quality products at reasonable prices back on the shelves soon. An iPhone 5 at the time of production cost about \u00a350-\u00a380 to produce and they've all been around that price since. I know this as I've studied Product Design and our Lecturer worked through getting one put together as if he was Apple, there are design costs too but with the sales of the phone, they become extremely small. So after all the costs surrounding designing, making, distributing, sales, they were making anything from 150% to 300% markup... I don't think it should be free phones, I understand they need to make a profit, but the price hikes are huge, but what we are receiving is actually not that proportion better. Moore's Law says that tech halves in price or doubles in speed or quality every 2 years (now closer to 2 and a half) This should mean that iPhones get cheaper overall or not go up in price much.\nLong rant over.\nLove the vids, please keep going, I'm a total tech lover, and iPhone or not, it's your money, your life, enjoy whatever tech you have!
Meanwhile I still use LG G3 which I can't root, and if not for the authenticator, Steam Guard, and Internet I would be able to live with a Nokia 3310.

Nice you pointed out that you don't need the 3D sensor for the Animoji. Didn't see any reviewers point that out. And it's the same thing with swipe-left/right at bottom to switch apps. Other iPhones can do that if it was programmed in the software. -- That Apple restricts some features/possibilities within the software to make their flagship \more\ special is just disappointing. 

I've always used iPhone since 3GS model. I love iPhones (having owned also 4, 6 plus, and now SE), and mostly the reason of why I've been sticking to it is the ecosystem (together with iPad and Macs). Besides, upgrading to 4 was worth it (retina and front camera). Upgrading to 6 plus was worth it (bigger screen+battery finally). Buying SE (missed smaller sized phone). And now, I miss the bigger screen and planning to upgrade, but so far I'm not convinced if X is worth it. 

Is Animoji worth the extra cost? For me personally, No. Sure it's fun to have, but I don't need that.. Is Face ID worth the extra cost? Maybe it's more convenient, but like mentioned in the review, Touch ID works the same if not better and I don't mind using a finger to unlock the phone. 

Sure I could go for the 8 or 8 plus, but the design though with the same huge bezels. After all I pointed out, the ONLY reason for me to still buy an iPhone for my next phone is the ecosystem it is part of. Which leaves me the question: Do I really need a phone that is part of that ecosystem? I often use my phone to edit documents on iCloud, and I have headphones that take advantage of the W1 chip. Are these two features worth sacrificing for a new exciting experience with an Android-phone, or should I go for the 8/X that doesn't really offer any changes I have use for?

I would pay something like 700 € for this, since Galaxy S8 is already widely available for 600 € in Europe. S8 has 3,5 mm jack, no notch, arguably a better screen, fingerprint sensor, no wobling on a flat surface and such refinements.

If you compare X to Note 8 you will get the pen and larger and better screen. Not that I accept the atrocious price of Note 8, but still.

So given the price, which you cannot ignore, this phone is one of the worst releases in mobile phone history and I cannot believe people are buying this and telling themselves this phone is even decent. 

Of course I myself could release a new phone which is a tad better in every category than this - and those phones already exist - then put on a price tag of 1600 € and get raving reviews, but that one would still suck because it offers so little for a critically high price.

Reviewers should stomp this phone to the ground, but yet I hear much praise. This is only because of the status that Apple still currenly owns, but only a fool would buy X for just that status.

No one really explained why they don\u2019t notice the notch when they use the phone. I have a theory: no one really does look at the status bar constantly. All the focus goes to the middle of the screen. It\u2019s also scientifically proven that the moment a person sees something new, their initial focus is all in the middle. That\u2019s why it\u2019s hard for some people to realise the big picture or their minds choose to see one thing when the whole thing is the correct perception. Going back to the notch, your focus stays in the middle of the screen. The only time you\u2019d notice the notch is when you are deliberately looking for something in the status bar. Be it time, battery, or network connection, you still don\u2019t look at those things constantly. That\u2019s why the notch seems to \u201cdisappear\u201d in use. Obviously, the notch doesn\u2019t literally disappear, but rather, our minds choose not to see the notch on top. That\u2019s why the notch is not a problem at all. If you come to think about it, the notch and ears are just merely extensions of the new screen. Don\u2019t think of it as a lose, but as a gain. You get extra screen on top, which can be used for then new status bar.

I like the iPhone X! I got to put my hands on one at Best Buy. I took to the home gesture immediately, but I couldn't get the \pick up and toss\ app switcher gesture. All in all it's a great iPhone. But, my 6s is still going strong, so I'm going to hold onto that. My 6s is my first ever iPhone after 6 years of Android phones, and while I miss some of Android's extra features, I like the stability of iOS. I have never had an Android phone not shit the bed after 12-18 months. It's just what Android does, it collapses under its own weight and bloat. A factory reset usually sorts it for a while, but then it's not gonna go another 12-18 months, more like 3-4 if you're lucky. I'm constantly blown away that my iPhone continues to be good. And I'm still blown away that having an icon below or to the right of a blank space is so hard for Apple. For a smartphone, particularly a big one, screen content should flow from the bottom to the top from user operated controls to content that is merely meant to be viewed. If I'm meant to interact with it, it should be closer to the bottom. If I'm not, push it to the top. So naturally I want my icons along the bottom, but not so much along the top.

Hey Marquees, been a fan since forever. I've seen this trend amongst the top YouTubers in recent years, (includes you) of not being critical enough. Even criticism is kind of sugar coated.

I'm considering the iPhone X for my mom, but I've come across the following criticisms (read on reddit) which unfortunately neither you, nor others have even touched.

1. The insane repair cost of front/back panel.

2. The turtle-slow wireless charging and slow fast charging (saw mrwhoseyourboss's video) and the exclusion of fast charging.

3. The strategy to sell 256 GB by not offering 128 GB. Should be informed imo, coz well, with 4k @ 60 fps, we all know how easy it is to full your storage. 

4. The bugs in iOS 11 which makes it seem like a beta, which makes the phone slower than the Android flagships. (A lot of discussions over reddit on this)

5. A word on comparison between the amoled of the X and the one on the Samsungs.

6. Whether the 8 plus makes more sense over the X. 

I know there's an intangible force  that doesn't allow YouTubers to be hyper-critical of the iPhones, but these ought to be covered. Unfortunately, I was hearing the same stuff what I've heard a million times over. The good.

iPhone X is going to be obsolete by the time machine learning helps the camera / Face ID get anywhere close to the Pixel 2, and probably also before all apps are updated for the notch (some apps take years on things like this). Swiping is slower and less convenient than tapping, and Face ID is slower and less convenient than Touch ID. Even if the speed and accuracy improves, it's still a pain to have to hold your phone up to your face to unlock it. You can unlock phones with fingerprint readers while you're picking them up or taking them out of your pocket...

Getting to the top corners is really tricky on this phone, and the reachability gesture is ironically hard to trigger with one hand. Watching video is flat out bad on this phone because you're either getting massive bezels and a small image, or a notch cutout. iOS is... iOS.

It does do a lot really well (processor/performance, camera, etc.) but this just isn't worth $1,000. It feels like sacrifices on top of sacrifices as opposed to the most premium experience money can buy. If someone handed me one of these tomorrow I would sell it without a second thought. $1,000 is like 140 burritos (or >150 if we're buying the fast charger, which hilariously isn't included). I guarantee you I would be happier with my current phone and 140 burritos.

I just haven't jumped on the bezel-less smartphone train yet. I mean, obviously it looks modern and looks cleaner, but bezels to me are treated just the same as the notch here for the iPhone X: I don't notice them. I have a Pixel 2 (non XL). I really wanted to get the XL because of the small bezels, but I hate big phones. Before this, I had an iPhone 6s and I convinced myself that I could get the regular Pixel 2 because, just like Marques mentioned about the notch, I'm not looking at the bezels when I was using the phone. Lo and behold, not once have I complained about the larger bezels on my Pixel because they just kind of melt away. So the $1000 for a bezel-less screen just isn't worth it to me.

Dude...........dude.......... I will first and openly admit, before I get a bunch of apple fans and Android haters, no phone is worth 1000 dollars. The functionality and look hasn't changed since the iPhone 5. I'm talking about color and art design. The cameras while impressive for all phones to fight, is really good. This one is probably just as impressive but man seriously? The price went up for, what to me at least as a over all user, an oled display and now a top firing speaker to run a duel speaker config. And not even good. I'm not even a Samsung fan boy anymore because even then I don't justify the design and other things that are not about this phone right now. While everyone has a right to spend their money on whatever they want and while I am clearly nobody to believe that this phone is useless to anyone except myself, I still can't believe you approved so little about this phone to justify $1000. There seriously has to be a line where enough is enough or this case there isn't enough to justify this price or idea that this is appropriate to the audience. But I digress as I prefer having a verbal conversation or rant about how I feel towards this phone than continue. Plus I am actually curious to see what thoughts and or mean comments I'm going to get for this one comment. Not trying to troll but from someone who expects a lot from an iPhone and apple themselves, I seriously am disappointed in this phone and this review. But maybe I'm not seeing the bigger picture. Someone can feel free to educate me a little as even I can be ignorant to the subject. Not a challenge or troll but just seriously wanting to hear a counter argument.
